        <h2>Understanding the HPTU Grading System: SGPA and CGPA</h2>
        <p>Techncial universities like HPTU use the Choice Based Credit System (CBCS). When you check your HPTU result, you will encounter terms that are different from traditional percentages. It is essential to understand them properly:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Credit Points:</strong> Each subject is assigned a specific number of credits based on its importance and complexity.</li>
            <li><strong>Grade Points:</strong> Your performance in a subject is ranked on a 10-point scale (O, A+, A, B+, B, C, P, F).</li>
            <li><strong>SGPA (Semester Grade Point Average):</strong> This is the weighted average of the grade points you earned in a single semester.</li>
            <li><strong>CGPA (Cumulative Grade Point Average):</strong> This is the average of all SGPAs earned up to the current point in your degree. A high CGPA is often a requirement for campus placements at major tech firms like TCS, Infosys, and Wipro.</li>
            <li><strong>Backlog/Supple:</strong> If you receive an 'F' grade in any subject, it will be listed as a backlog in your HPTU result, and you will need to reappear for that specific exam in the subsequent session.</li>
        </ul>

